external_knowledge:
- "Top 10 queries" refers to the queries with the highest average execution time within each application;
- "Have been commented on" means the queries have at least one comment;
- "Ranked by their average execution time" means the queries are ordered from the slowest to the fastest.

- 'slow-moving giants' refers to queries with an average execution time greater than 1000 milliseconds;
- 'whispers of wisdom' refers to comments about the queries;
- The date range '2023-01-01' to '2023-02-01' is used to filter comments within that period.

- "Frequently executed" means the queries have been run more than 5 times;
- "Often take more than 500 milliseconds to complete" means the queries have more than 2 instances where the execution time exceeds 500 milliseconds;
- "Cumulative average execution time" is the running average execution time of these queries, calculated over their IDs.

- 'fast_query' refers to queries that are known to execute quickly;
- 'rare_query' refers to queries that are not frequently executed;
- 'user_id = 1' refers to a specific user identified by the ID 1.

- "Optimized queries" are queries that have been improved for better performance;
- "Flown more swiftly" refers to having a shorter execution time;
- "Dawn of 2022" refers to the start of the year 2022 (January 1, 2022);
- "Average unoptimized queries" refers to the average execution time of all queries that have not been optimized.

sql:
SELECT query_text, execution_time
FROM queries
ORDER BY execution_time DESC;

external_knowledge:
- 'Blog Website' is the name of a specific web application in the database;
- 'Most time-consuming queries' refers to the queries with the highest execution times;
- 'Bloom' is a metaphor for query execution;
- 'Petals' is a metaphor for the rows affected by the query.

- 'Soared to the top of the ratings' refers to queries with a rating of 4.0 or higher;
- 'Top three performers' refers to queries with a performance rank of 3 or lower;
- 'Query dependency network' refers to queries found in the `query_dependencies` table.

- Best-performing queries are determined by the lowest execution time and memory usage;
- Each web application has a unique identifier (app_id) that links queries to their respective applications;
- Recommendations are provided for queries to improve performance.

- "Web application garden" refers to a collection of web applications managed in the database;
- "Cumulative execution time" is the sum of the execution times of all queries for each application, accumulated over time;
- "Total cumulative execution time" is the sum of all cumulative execution times across all applications.

- Slow queries are defined as those taking more than 1000 milliseconds to execute;
- CPU-hungry queries have an average CPU usage greater than 100%;
- The query also retrieves associated comments to provide context on performance issues.

- 'Optimized queries' refer to queries that have had at least one optimization applied;
- Performance metrics include average, maximum, and minimum execution times;
- The results are sorted by the number of optimizations in descending order.

- "blossomed with the fruits of optimization" refers to queries that have been optimized and have corresponding entries in the `query_optimization` table;
- "the average time they take to bloom" refers to the average execution time of the queries;
- "the total bounty of their optimization efforts" refers to the sum of the optimization benefits.

- 'cast by Jane Smith' refers to the user name 'Jane Smith' in the `users` table;
- 'spells of great power' refers to the query types 'SELECT', 'INSERT', 'UPDATE', 'DELETE';
- 'taken more than a second to complete their incantations' refers to the total execution time of the queries being greater than 1000 milliseconds.

sql:
SELECT app_name
FROM web_applications
ORDER BY app_created_at DESC;

SELECT COUNT(query_id) AS total_queries_executed
FROM query_history
WHERE user_id = 1;

